There are several degenerate vibrational levels (υ = 0, 1, 2, etc.) for each state (S0, S1, S2, etc.) of the electron. During absorption or emission, the electron can move from any vibrational level of a state to any vibrational level of other states. The transition from υ = 0 of the S0 state to υ = 1 of the S1 state is the utmost favorable Frank-Condon transition [36]. The PL peak position is blue-shifted with increasing in the synthesis temperature from 160 to 200 ℃ (Fig. 9a
                        ). The blue shifting occurs due to decreasing the size of CQDs with rising in the synthesis temperature [29]. This blue shift is caused by the reduction in size of the CQDs as the synthesis temperature rises. The TEM results also show the reduction of the size with increasing the synthesis temperature. which is supported by the TEM results. However, the PL intensity is increased with an increase in the synthesis temperature (Fig. 9b). Furthermore, the PL emission peaks of all the three CQDs obtained at the excitation wavelength of 380 nm were de-convoluted using Lorentz-Gaussian fit. Each peak is de-convoluted into five peaks, however, only three peaks are dominated (Fig. 10a
                        –c).
